{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"303645f6-a3a5-4a47-93cb-53a24831c465","content":"Here's how to migrate:\n\n1. **Remove** the `xunit.runner.visualstudio` package reference.\n\n2. **Add** these packages:\n   ```xml\n   <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Platform\" Version=\"1.*\" />\n   <PackageReference Include=\"xunit.runner.microsofttestingplatform\" Version=\"1.*\" />\n   ```\n\n3. **Add** this property to your `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup>\n     <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n\n4. **Enable** the test platform in your `.csproj` (generates the entry point automatically):\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup>\n     <GenerateTestingPlatformEntryPoint>true</GenerateTestingPlatformEntryPoint>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n\n5. **Run tests** with:\n   ```\n   dotnet test\n   ```\n   Or directly via the built executable.\n\n**Key notes:**\n- Your existing `[Fact]` / `[Theory]` tests remain unchanged — no test code changes needed.\n- If you use `dotnet test`, the `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport` property ensures compatibility.\n- You can optionally set `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` to run tests as a standalone executable.\n\nWould you like help applying these changes to a specific `.csproj` file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"346ca930-689b-47ad-9f9a-54807ae3fd3e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate their xUnit.net project from VSTest (using xunit.runner.visualstudio) to Microsoft.Testing.Platform. Let me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge of this migration path.","outputTokens":421},"id":"23491f27-3ad4-483f-978e-137be76e2ef3","timestamp":"2026-04-07T14:20:49.483Z","parentId":"76ccaef4-1454-4914-8efe-064542845cf4"}
